 funds? How can one argue <br>that the borrowed funds were subject to the tax paid by the borrower?</p><p><font style="font-size: 12px;"><b>Posted by joseph miller on Jan. 21, 2012 at 03:15 PM</b></font></p></div><div><p>Josh G: you are double taxed on the interest. if there were no taxes your <br>interest would be $5k, not $3750. Because your principal has already been <br>taxed, the interest has also been implicity taxed at your 25% rate, giving you <br>only 3750. and then you have to pay another 25% on the 3750. that is called <br>double taxation. do the math.</p><p><font style="font-size: 12px;"><b>Posted by sky jumper on Jan. 27, 2012 at 02:14 PM</b></font></p></div><div><p>Why is it so difficult to see that Capital Gains is NOT double taxed? Think <br>about it like this - whatever you initially invest is never taxed again, only <br>the 'income' created by the already taxed money...and this is called <br>'interest.' THIS is the money that is taxed.<br><br>At present this is the best area for rich people to make money and is perceived <br>as a 'loop hole' to pay less money on their investments....might also suggest <br>why the economy wont grow from 'trickle down' economics (financially better to <br>invest this way).</p><p><font style="font-size: 12px;"><b>Posted by Alan Jones on Jan. 29, 2012 at 03:09 AM</b></font></p></div><div><p>Alan Jones - your thought process is incomplete and reflects a mindset that the <br>tax you pay isn't really "your" money to begin with. To fully appreciate this <br>you must imagine a world without taxes - and how you would use your extra <br>wealth. If you are the type to spend the extra cash then that would explain <br>your point of view. <br><br>You are also ignoring several other dynamics - including the impact of <br>inflation on real returns, and the impact of corporate taxes on stock returns. <br><br>The real problem here is that we as a society are programmed to accept heavy <br>taxation as a fact of life, and policy makers are taking full advantage of <br>it.</p><p><font style="font-size: 12px;"><b>Posted by sky jumper on Feb. 1, 2012 at 10:08 PM</b></font></p></div><div><p>Ah yes a country with no taxes, can you imagine. The lack of roads, schools, <br>police, fireman and every other service that our tax dollars pay for. Who needs <br>to be educated or protected, surely not I.</p><p><font style="font-size: 12px;"><b>Posted by Guy person on Feb. 3, 2012 at 12:27 AM</b></font></p></div><div><p>Ah yes, because that's exactly what I was advocating - a world without taxes so <br>uneducated people can entirely miss the point of a reasoned argument. <br><br>If you were to actually do the math instead of making snide remarks you would <br>see that single taxation on the principal+gain *after* the gains are realized <br>actually yields more tax revenues for the government AND more retained wealth <br>for investors. That's because there would be more captial at work to create <br>wealth. But I guess you missed that...</p><p><font style="font-size: 12px;"><b>Posted by sky jumper on Feb. 3, 2012 at 12:52 PM</b></font></p></div><div><p>Sky jumper- income was generated by two different actions...say I'm an <br>ex-president and make $100,000 for giving a speech and then instead of putting <br>the remaining 75k (after 25% taxes) in a bank to earn interest I buy a plane <br>for 75k and in my spare time I take people for rides in it...I charge them <br>$3750...Shouldn't I pay 25% on the $3750 plane ride income? What If fly the <br>75k plane for 100 trips and generate 100 x $3750 = $375,000? Should that $375k <br>income not be taxed because I already paid 25% on the original 100k speaking <br>fee? It's easier to make $3750 for just letting someone else use the 75k money <br>for a year, but my point is that whether I'm flying a plane or letting someone <br>borrow my money there are two actions generating two separate sources of <br>income.</p><p><font style="font-size: 12px;"><b>Posted by earth walker 