ed to make sure <br>they are not double dipping. and when you take a real close look you can see <br>they in fact are.</p><p><font style="font-size: 12px;"><b>Posted by sky jumper on Feb. 4, 2012 at 11:23 PM</b></font></p></div><div><p>sky jumper - I'm trying to get my mind around what you're saying...it's <br>difficult for me though because it seems like the people who are creating cash <br>flow via labor are subject to tax on their income, but people who generate cash <br>flow via investment are not (that is, if capital gains weren't taxed). I do <br>follow you though on the matter of the government actually collecting more <br>revenue if they wait to tax income until it has a longer period of time to be <br>productive in the economy (however; a full comparison would have to take into <br>account what the government does with the revenue it collects)...Let me ask you <br>this: If the corporate tax rate was 0% would it then be appropriate to tax <br>capital gains at the same rate as income earned via labor? Thank you for your <br>polite response.</p><p><font style="font-size: 12px;"><b>Posted by earth walker on Feb. 5, 2012 at 06:44 PM</b></font></p></div><hr></div><p><b><a href="/taxcom/taxblog.nsf/Comment?OpenForm&amp;ParentUNID=DEF66D321B470B4E85257926004A2E78#form">Comment</a></b></p>
